,Recommended,262120,10293839,"Posted: 30 May, 2014",all,Clegg Buvins,"PROS- Tower defence with fully 3D environments, creeps and weapon behaviors- Turrets are varied and use ballistics, as well as AI aiming, instead of automatic guaranteed damage outputs- Player can control fully fleshed out turrets or vehicles to take part in the defence, not just a gimmick- GI Joe/Cold War 1980s trimmings, with historical weapons and creeps and a good amount of tongue-in-cheek- Visuals and sound are excellent (for a game from 2011) Players can also joyfully destroy most level features, leaving levels looking war torn.CONS- World War 1 content, whilst expanded, is inferior to the original Toy Soldiers game. Game breaking bugs etc- Multiplayer issues - DO NOT EXPECT ONLINE MULTIPLAYER TO WORK, split screen is great fun- Will not appeal to those fond of tower defence games full of numbers and fixed variables, or players who don't find the ""random and whacky"" nature of AI aiming and projectile physics to be enjoyable.If you're a tower defense fan but tired of strict grid-and-number affairs, give Toy Soldiers a try. If you've got any interest in 20th century military history, give Toy Soldiers a try.Instead of coldly precise towers on a grid issuing 10 points of damage every 2.5 seconds to the nearest creep, Toy Soldiers has machine guns snaking lead around the heads of Russian troops, or surface-to-air missiles casting smoky trails as they home in on supersonic US Tomcat jets. A proper realtime game with physics and 3D projectiles instead of simply disguised dice rolls hitting HP sponges.As opposed to weighing up number based tower upgrades, area-of-effects and watching hundreds of creeps marching in a static laneway Toy Soldiers brings real time chaos and player controlled action to the mix. Build your turrets and watch their various attacks interact with the environment and enemy waves without the spreadsheet-precision of regular TD games. Take control of turrets yourself and chain up combos to unleash powerful player controlled call-ins, or hop into a vacant helicopter or tank to sweep the battlefield clean of enemies yourself.Oozing with charm and  great ""modelling diorama"" asthetics Toy Soldiers is a breakout from the tower defense mould. Containing both the grim madness of the WW1 Western Front as well as the over-the-top 1980s Cold War, Toy Soldiers is a delightful mix of historical homage and video game fun. Contains the best representation of WW1 in a game I've seen, though perhaps the original, un-tweaked Toy Soldiers game nails it better. Only time will tell if TS:C improves or degrades the WW1 content.[UPDATE - Sadly it seems that the World War 1 content is doomed to be buggy and generally inferior to the original, but such is the effect of porting an older game into a newer game engine. Still, the very well polished Cold War aspect of the game is extremely worth the purchase.]"
