,Recommended,262120,18560950,"Posted: 18 October, 2015",all,Oregono,"Time to completion - Around 15 hoursWhat I played - Every mission (campaign and expansion) on normal. Minus 1 mission (More on that later).Toy Soliders Complete is the original Toy Soldiers tower defense game along with its 2 expansions and the Cold War stand-alone with it's two expansions.Tower Defense, eh?The basic game loop:- You can place turrets in specific locations. Certain turrets (like ani-air and artillery) require larger spaces. Upgrade turrets and fend off the invading forces.## The main difference here is that you can both directly control any turret giving you more accuracy and better kill counts, as well as using various level-specific vehicles which run on batteries.Pros:- Great aesthetic. Love the fact that all the levels are like in a kids room.- Level design is generally good. Sometimes i was able to place down turrets and then sit back for a round or two and let them go to down on stuff. Other times, there were bosses that would instant kill my turrets. But overall, I feel it was well done.-Lots of levels.- Survival and vs modes (didnt play vs),The Bad- Over the course of the game, I ran into 2 hard crashes to desktop and one instance where an enemy soldier didnt move and I had to hunt him down after the level was basically over. Over the course of 15 hours this doesnt seem like a huge deal.- I literally cant play the last mission of the main cold war campaign because it hard crashes to desktop on the loading screen. So thats annoying. Beat everything else though with no simialr issues,Overall:While this is still in early access, it generally feels like a finished game with a few annoying bugs, Gameplay-wise I say it is worth it. I am a bit annoyed I cant play one level, but thats one in a lot, so whatever. I do hope they fix it."
76561198087077872,Recommended,262120,33745067,Posted: 23 July,all,Pappagiorgio,"Buggy, yet quite unique take on the tower defense genre. Unfortunately, it left Early Access too soon and seems more-or-less abandoned at this point, as if the devs had decided to prioritize other titles instead. Scumbag move! But if this game works for you and the bugs aren't too distracting, like the lack of music in-game, then it's hard to put down. The units are all awesome, and you can take direct control of ALL of them, and then of some other extra air and ground units at your disposal, so you can take matter on your own hands if things get to hectic, like a F-14 Tomcat, an Apache helicopter, WWI era tanks or the Red Baron's own aircraft just to mention some. From WWI to the Cold War, there's lots of content here and factions, all DLCs for both games are already included, so lots of hours of fun.Quite strategic in its use of units and upgrades, since every upgrade comes with side effects, like longer reloading times for WWI era artillery, or with different effects in the case of modern American artillery -spread instead of direct ammo/howitzer with precise munitions vs barrage of MLRS- or a mortar emplacement with bio-chemical ammo that later can be turned into a flamethrower and then into a regular mortar with napalm effects, each with their own pluses and cons. To add variety to an already varied game, you can make use of random special powers, abilities and you can also take control of a hero, but it's not really necessary, and that's only if you manage to obtain them by killing enemy units directly in a combo. The bosses are awesome, they're these humongous machines that dwarf any other units so they're always fun and interesting to fight.Having said that, I would give this game a neutral rating due to the Early Access blunder and amount of bugs, and the lack of in-game music really pisses me off. But this being Steam, it's either a thumbs down a thumbs up, so I'm going with a positive rating overall since I did indeed enjoy my time with Toy Soldiers: Complete."
76561198029496191,Not Recommended,262120,10049416,"Posted: 7 May, 2014",all,Dr. FeelGoose,"""This game is awesome. The exclusion or better yet elimanition of GFWL in this game makes it playable in offline mode which is a plus. I should've known this was coming out before I bought the first one, could've saved money....but TS: Cold War is only on PC through this game. I can't wait for them to include TS 1. There is a lot of bugs and the game does crash ocasionally, but this is in Early Access so what do you expect? This a defenite buy here.""No, it's not a defenite buy. Take a look at my new review for this game:Toy Soldiers Complete....what can I say about it. Well I can say  it's only half of a good game.  Cold War is awesome, it has explosions, easy to learn mechanics, and overall good gameplay (and the DLC is free!).  There are a few issues in Cold War but are not very noticeable. TS1 in this game....sucks.  There are so many problems with TS1 in this game.  I own the original Toy Soldiers, so when I bought TS:C I expected TS1 to be an exact port, but I was wrong.  SO MANY GLITCHES can be found in TS1 in this game, and even after a new update comes out some glitches still remain unfixed (and continuously remain unfixed even after constant updates).  Signal Studios tried to combine what they did in Cold War in their ""remastered"" version of TS1,  by adding Turbo Charge, Barrages, and other things, but these additions only reduced the quality of the game.  The barrages in the TS:C version of TS1 are just the Cold War barrages but polished to look different, and I'm pretty sure World War I nor Toy Soldiers 1 had an orbital laser, it's just madness!   Signal Studios should've just stuck to their guns, but they justhadto add something new.  I get that Signal Studios wanted to balance the games so in VS. mode one team couldn't have a higher advantage over the other, but what they did here was just terrible. Here is a list of 10 glitches and inaccuracies in this version of TS1 included in this game:1) Whenever the Chemical Level 3 is used, it leaves behind the gas cloud and it loops over and over.2) Whenever the Machine Gun Level 3 is used, the muzzle can be quite blinding.3) Some enemy units are overpowered and have way too much health.4) The Anti-Air guns have this annoying gravity bullet velocity that forces you to shoot higher and due to this renders the Anti-Air gun's AI to be completely useless.5) The Anti-Tank guns are just the models of the Level 3 Anti-Infantry guns taken from the original TS1.6) TS1 bosses have a bit too little health.7) The Machine Gun models are also taken from TS1, which is ok, but the models are from the wrong parts of the game.8) The Sniper Tower is really just a Machine Gun Level 2 but modified.9) The Mortars have the same effects from Cold War.10) The sounds for the Chemicals Levels 1 and 2 are swapped.There's plenty more glitches and inaccuracies in this version of TS1.  If you want Cold War on PC,  go ahead, buy this acursed thing. If you don't have TS1 and instead buy this game thinking it has the original TS1, you'll be very disappointed.  The only thing that's worth buying in this game is Cold War, but that's about it. This game is only half good and half completed. Cold War is ok; but TS1 in this game sucks. If I were you, I wouldn't buy it. Instead I'd wait for Toy Soldiers: War Chest to come out and then buy the original, 100% authentic, no doubt about it, not sheet TS1 on PC. The original TS1 does have Windows Live Arcade and it forces you to play online, but just deal with it, be glad it has SteamWorks at least.Thank goodness Ubisoft is making the next Toy Soldiers, because I think they will do a whole lot better job than Signal Studios ever did with this damn game.  I know this game is still in Early Access, but this is just lousy.4.8/10"
